===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# Either of {{taxlink|Bubalus quarlesi|species|noshow=1|ver=161205}} or {{taxlink|Bubalus depressicornis|species|noshow=1|ver=161205}}, being a small [[Indonesian]] [[water buffalo]] similar in appearance to a [[deer]].
#* '''1998''', Jane Whitten, ''Tropical Wildlife of Southeast Asia'', [http://books.google.com.au/books?id=psuWpwZuX_oC&pg=PA16&dq=%22anoa%22%7C%22anoas%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=NfwOUrTNMOvtiAeLzYDgCg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22anoa%22%7C%22anoas%22&f=false page 16],
#*: '''Anoas''' need undisturbed forest and cannot adapt to logged areas. The bad-tempered '''anoa''' with its sharp short horns is greatly feared, but in spite of this it is periodically suggested as a potential domestic animal. Anyone who has met with an '''anoa''' ridicules this idea.
#* '''2000''', Michael Alvard, ''The Impact of Traditional Subsistence Hunting and Trapping on Prey Populations: Data from Wana Horticuluralists of Upland Central Sulwesi, Indonesia'', John G. Robinson, Elizabeth L. Bennett (editors), ''Hunting for Sustainability in Tropical Forests'', [http://books.google.com.au/books?id=ZawmOh3IZ_IC&pg=PA223&dq=%22anoa%22%7C%22anoas%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=NfwOUrTNMOvtiAeLzYDgCg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22anoa%22%7C%22anoas%22&f=false page 223],
#*: The Celebes pig and, to a lesser degree, the anoa were the focus of the Wana's large game interests.
#* '''2011''', Colin Groves, Peter Grubb, ''Ungulate Taxonomy'', [http://books.google.com.au/books?id=XAX0bqw-I2oC&pg=PT168&dq=%22anoa%22%7C%22anoas%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=NfwOUrTNMOvtiAeLzYDgCg&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22anoa%22%7C%22anoas%22&f=false unnumbered page],
#*: They reported seeing mountain '''anoa''' trophies for sale, and also a living captive animal, in the Toraja highlands; probable lowland '''anoas''' in the Gunung Tangkoko National Park on the N tip of Sulawesi, and evidence of both kinds of '''anoas''' in or near the Dumoga-Bone National Park.

